[normal].  
[normal]ADCS is the professional association for directors of children's services an
[normal]d their senior management teams.
[normal] 
[normal]Under the Children Act 2004, the DCS
[normal] 
[normal]is
[normal] the 
[normal]chief
[normal] officer responsible for the 
[normal]discharge of local authority functions for children’s social care
[normal]. T
[normal]he DCS provides a clear and unambiguous line of 
[normal]professional
[normal] accountability for children’s services as well
[normal] being 
[normal]professional
[normal]ly responsible
[normal] for the leadership, strategy and effectiveness of local authority children’s services and, as such, has a particular interest in the 
[normal]publication of the Ofsted Social Care Annual Report. 
[normal]ADCS 
[normal]believe
[normal]s
[normal] that inspection
[normal], by Ofsted
[normal], of the local authority, has
[normal] the potential to be helpful
[normal] if it supports improvement in outcomes f
[normal]or children and their families and 
[normal]our response is set in this context.
[normal]2012 – 13 was the first year that the Ofsted Annual Report has been split into two separate publications, one encom
[normal]passing 
[normal]social care exclusively and another, published in early December 2013, focusing predominantly on the education aspect of Ofsted’s remit. It is not clear what benefit this brings to the workforce
[normal] or the public
[normal], but the publication of two reports 
[normal]sep
[normal]arating the local authority’s work in respect of children’s social care from that of its role in quality assuring  school standards
[normal], does not reflect the co-dependencies that exist
[normal] 
[normal]when improving outcomes for children and young people.
[normal]A
[normal]DCS welcomes Ofsted
[normal]’s focus on improving standards in children’s social care. All directors of children’s services
[normal], whether their services have been judged
[normal] by Ofs
[normal]t
[normal]ed
[normal] to be 
[normal]‘
[normal]outstanding
[normal]’
[normal] or 
[normal]‘
[normal]inadequate
