[normal]On publication of the Ofsted Annual Report, Sir Michael
[normal] Wilshaw
[normal] called for 
[normal]“strong and stable leadership to bring about sustained improvement in the help
[normal],
[normal] care and protection of ou
[normal]r most vulnerable young people”, ADCS agrees with this laudable aim and acknowledges the crucial 
[normal]role of
[normal] strong and stable leadership teams, not exclusively the director of children’s services but also the wider management team
[normal],
[normal] in delivering good, sustain
[normal]able services. Yet 
[normal]Ofsted's approach to inspection, namely the single word judgment, is not conducive to 
[normal]leadership stability
[normal]. A judgment of inadequate
[normal] after the inspection of local authority children’s services
[normal], and the subsequent instability this can cau
[normal]se, can be detrimental to the improvement journey of a local authority.
[normal] In one local authority, the vacancy rate amongst children’s social workers 
[normal]increased from 4% to 40% after a judgment of “inadequate”. Other children’s services departments, such as Bir
[normal]mingham City Council, 
[normal]have publically stated the impact that staff 
[normal]vacancies has had when trying to improve their service. 
[normal]A 
[normal]move to 
[normal]narrative judgment
[normal]s, as opposed to a single word judgment,
[normal] would allow local authorities to work with their local partner
[normal]s
[normal],
[normal] including health, police and education
[normal], in a less punitive environment
[normal] to form an action plan to  i
[normal]mprove
[normal] services
[normal] in their local area. 
[normal]Helping, protecting and caring for vulnerable children, young people and their families is a complex multi agency 
[normal]business that is not eased by the febrile climate that children’s services leaders sometimes find themselves in during the immediate aftermath of an ‘inadequate’ inspection judgment.
